04590nam a22006135i 9780674269675DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742696757 a10.4159/97806742696752doi  a(DE-B1597)600628  a(OCoLC)1264275274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh1 aGallagher, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNazis of Copley Square :bThe Forgotten Story of the Christian Front /cCharles Gallagher. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. The Idea of a Christian Front -- tCHAPTER 2. Soldiers for the Body of Christ -- tCHAPTER 3. Terror in the Name of Christ -- tCHAPTER 4. What’s the Matter with Me? -- tCHAPTER 5. A Rather Bold -- tCHAPTER 6. A Nazi in Boston -- tCHAPTER 7. Hitler’s Spymaster on Beacon Hill -- tCHAPTER 8. Rifles and Rhetoric -- tCHAPTER 9. Kissing Hitler -- tCHAPTER 10. Questions of the Most Delicate Kind -- tCHAPTER 11. Underground -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe forgotten history of American terrorists who, in the name of God, conspired to overthrow the government and formed an alliance with Hitler. On January 13, 1940, FBI agents burst into the homes and offices of seventeen members of the Christian Front, seizing guns, ammunition, and homemade bombs. J. Edgar Hoover’s charges were incendiary: the group, he alleged, was planning to incite a revolution and install a “temporary dictatorship” in order to stamp out Jewish and communist influence in the United States. Interviewed in his jail cell, the front’s ringleader was unbowed: “All I can say is—long live Christ the King! Down with communism!” In Nazis of Copley Square, Charles Gallagher provides a crucial missing chapter in the history of the American far right. The men of the Christian Front imagined themselves as crusaders fighting for the spiritual purification of the nation, under assault from godless communism, and they were hardly alone in their beliefs. The front traced its origins to vibrant global Catholic theological movements of the early twentieth century, such as the Mystical Body of Christ and Catholic Action. The front’s anti-Semitism was inspired by Sunday sermons and by lay leaders openly espousing fascist and Nazi beliefs. Gallagher chronicles the evolution of the front, the transatlantic cloak-and-dagger intelligence operations that subverted it, and the mainstream political and religious leaders who shielded the front’s activities from scrutiny. Nazis of Copley Square offers a grim tale of faith perverted to violent ends, and its lessons provide a warning for those who hope to stop the spread of far-right violence today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aBritish Intelligence.  aDomestic terrorism.  aErnst Röhm.  aFather Charles E. Coughlin.  aForeign Agents Registration Act.  aHeinrich Himmler.  aJudeo-Bolshevism.  aNazi spying.  aSpecial Operations Executive.  aanti-Communism.  aright-wing extremism.  asedition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391140 cprintz978067498371740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067426967540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269675/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles